Tartine Bakery is one of those places you hear about even when you're not from SF. There's something about their presence that really draws people in, and I think it definitely has to do with the rustic nature of their pastries and desserts. For a joint that has such a strong presence, I was very happy to find that both the staff and the food maintained a very "down to Earth" vibe. The lines vary at different times of the day but moves relatively quickly. I ordered the ham quiche, ham croque monsieur, a banana cream pie, croissant, and coffee. Honestly it all incredibly delicious. The quiche and croque had that incredible "meatiness" that you normally just don't get at other places. With that said, it was also delicate in the sense that everything wasn't just a big creamy mess. It was light, delicious, and so so so fulfilling. I will say, however, that I do prefer the traditional croques that aren't open faced and normally I enjoy a touch of nutmeg just to emphasize the depth of the bechamel sauce. Besides that, they were excellent. The banana cream pie was quite nice and croissant was obviously flakey and incredible. Don't be afraid to stop by Tartine and see what its all about, theres a reason why they're viewed so highly! Looking forward to returning soon to try more of their baked goods!

This place could be a church because the food is heavenly. This place could be a cemetery because the bread is to die for. This place could be a post office because the line is out the door. After reading some Yelp reviews I thought I had a good idea of what I wanted and how to get it. The endless cup of coffee was my first priority to go with many baked goods. The Morning Bun was dreamy. It was like a cinnamon roll without the cinnamon, substitute orange. Normally orange flavor would put me off a tad but the pastry, texture flavor were so good, the somewhat subtle orange flavor did not over power. If these were donuts I would eat a dozen. The Croissant was going to get a multi level critical review. I've been to France and Costco and know the difference. It was superb. probably perfect. Fall apart crispy on the outside with moist delicate lace inside. You know the croissant is great by how many flakes hit the plate and yet not a one remains due to finishing them all. I took my time and enjoyed four cups of coffee, the nice lady behind the coffee corner threatening to cut me off. I had the Gougere, a cheesey puff with black pepper. It was airy like a Yorkshire pudding, but was hard to praise after the two previous pastries. Maybe it was more dinnery because it was savory. I learned during my visit that some bread is available during the day/morning whereas some is only fresh in the afternoon. Was glad there were several loves on the chalk board while I was there: Country $8.75 & Ancient Grain $9.75 I was impressed by the size of the loaf, almost double a typical bread, making it a good value. I actually enjoyed it days later because sometimes these naturally leavened doughs can improve with age. It was miraculous. Again, give me a dozen! If I lived in SF I would move to this neighborhood and gain 92 pounds.

I had heard of Tartine, but even after almost 3 years of living in the Bay Area, I had yet to step foot in the bakery. I eventually ventured there with a friend, and am so glad I did. Tartine is located off the beaten path on a corner that is quiet and unassuming. My friend and I were not sure at first if we were even walking up to the right place as there is no visible sign overhead. I like the fact that despite how well-known it is, it still feels small and quaint, like a bakery should. There was a line, but it wasn't too long and moved pretty quickly. The cases were full of tantalizing baked goods, from tarts and pies to pastries, croissants, quiche, and savory toasts topped with loads of cheese. My friend and I had such a hard time picking out what we wanted because everything looked so good! We eventually settled on splitting the coffee cake and another pastry that we think may have been a frangipane tart topped with caramelized grapefruit slices. Both choices were incredible! Lovely and slightly unique (in a good way) flavors and perfect textures - flakey pastry on the tart with a creamy but firm filing, and a soft delicate crumb on the coffee cake with some kind of a fruit purée layer in the center and the perfect crumb topping. The prices were a bit high - over $13 for the two pastries. I will definitely be back, but for the sake of my budget, I'll have to limit myself a bit.

    Tartine Bakery is one of those places you hear about even when you're not from SF. There's something about their presence that really draws people in, and I think it definitely has to do with the rustic nature of their pastries and desserts. For a joint that has such a strong presence, I was very happy to find that both the staff and the food maintained a very "down to Earth" vibe.

    The lines vary at different times of the day but moves relatively quickly. I ordered the ham quiche, ham croque monsieur, a banana cream pie, croissant, and coffee. Honestly it all incredibly delicious. The quiche and croque had that incredible "meatiness" that you normally just don't get at other places. With that said, it was also delicate in the sense that everything wasn't just a big creamy mess. It was light, delicious, and so so so fulfilling. I will say, however, that I do prefer the traditional croques that aren't open faced and normally I enjoy a touch of nutmeg just to emphasize the depth of the bechamel sauce. Besides that, they were excellent.

    The banana cream pie was quite nice and croissant was obviously flakey and incredible. Don't be afraid to stop by Tartine and see what its all about, theres a reason why they're viewed so highly! Looking forward to returning soon to try more of their baked goods!

The lemon meringue was very fresh, light and sweet. I would recommend this for those who want a chocolate-less dessert. Will be back to taste pastries and sandwiches next time!

    There's less space to sit inside and the all the tables are often be occupied. It's so close to Dolores park, I'd recommend grabbing something and walking over there to enjoy the food.

    I had heard of Tartine, but even after almost 3 years of living in the Bay Area, I had yet to step foot in the bakery. I eventually ventured there with a friend, and am so glad I did. Tartine is located off the beaten path on a corner that is quiet and unassuming. My friend and I were not sure at first if we were even walking up to the right place as there is no visible sign overhead. I like the fact that despite how well-known it is, it still feels small and quaint, like a bakery should. There was a line, but it wasn't too long and moved pretty quickly. The cases were full of tantalizing baked goods, from tarts and pies to pastries, croissants, quiche, and savory toasts topped with loads of cheese. My friend and I had such a hard time picking out what we wanted because everything looked so good! We eventually settled on splitting the coffee cake and another pastry that we think may have been a frangipane tart topped with caramelized grapefruit slices. Both choices were incredible! Lovely and slightly unique (in a good way) flavors and perfect textures - flakey pastry on the tart with a creamy but firm filing, and a soft delicate crumb on the coffee cake with some kind of a fruit purée layer in the center and the perfect crumb topping. The prices were a bit high - over $13 for the two pastries. I will definitely be back, but for the sake of my budget, I'll have to limit myself a bit.

    If you like cheese and are willing to wait in line for on average 30 minutes, Tartine is a place to try. Walkable distance to Dolores park, the place is pretty small and seating is only for those who have already ordered and are waiting for their orders.

    The sandwiches are around $13-14, and I don't even like cheese so I'm not the best critic on those, although I can say it is on the pricier side. My sister got the pecorino and almond sandwich which she didn't like too much because the cheese overpowered the rest of the ingredients

    I got a quiche which was too fluffy for my taste and alright, but the pastries we got we for the most part pretty good. The canelé de bordeaux had a slight burnt taste to it which is expected from the rum but it wasn't my favorite. The hazelnut cream tart and lemon cream tart were perfect and very cute too! The menu does have a lot of variety so I do think it's a hit or miss on what you order.
